{
  "title": "Benchmarking REST APIs using FastAPI with Python 3.12+",
  "summary": "This guide demonstrates how to measure the performance of your FastAPI-based REST APIs using Python 3.12+'s built-in benchmarking tools.",

  "key_points": [
    "FastAPI provides a built-in benchmarking feature that allows you to test the performance of your API endpoints.",
    "You can use Python 3.12+'s `timeit` module for more fine-grained control over benchmarks.",
    "It's essential to isolate and replicate test conditions for accurate benchmarking results."
  ],

  "code_examples": [
    {
      "language": "python",
      "code": "```\nfrom fastapi import FastAPI\napp = FastAPI()\n@app.get('/items/{item_id}')\ndef read_item(item_id: int):\treturn {'item': item_id}\nif __name__ == '__main__':\n    app.benchmark_app()``"
    },
    {
      "language": "python",
      "code": "```\nimport timeit\nstmt = 'my_function()'\nsetup = 'from my_module import my_function'\nprint(timeit.timeit(stmt, setup=setup, number=1000))``"
    }
  ],

  "version_notes": [
    "FastAPI version 0.73.0 introduced the `benchmark_app()` function.",
    "Python 3.12+ includes improvements in its built-in profiling and benchmarking tools."
  ],

  "caveats": [
    "Ensure to run benchmarks multiple times and average the results for better accuracy.",
    "Be aware of external factors that might influence your API's performance, such as database access or network latency.",
    "When using `timeit`, adjust `number` and `globals` parameters according to your specific use case."
  ]
}

